%I A394252 #16 Apr 03 2026 21:51:24
%S A394252 1,2,5,10,28,56,112,326,652,1304,2608,7712,15424,30848,61696,182480,
%T A394252 364960,729920,1459840,2919680,8697344,17394688,34789376,69578752,
%U A394252 139157504,414552832,829105664,1658211328,3316422656,6632845312,13265690624,39657914368
%N A394252 a(1)=1; for n>1, a(n) is the smallest integer greater than a(n-1) that cannot be written as the sum of exactly n-1 elements from {a(1),...,a(n-1)}, repetition allowed.
%C A394252 Among the first 32 computed terms several consecutive doubling blocks occur, for example 1,2; 5,10; 28,56,112; 326,652,1304,2608; 7712,15424,30848,61696; 182480,364960,729920,1459840,2919680. The lengths of these doubling blocks appear to increase over time (2,2,3,4,4,5,...), and the number of blocks of a given length also appears to increase, although with irregular fluctuations. No proof of these structural properties is known to the author.
%C A394252 Empirical observation: a(n+1) appears to be either 2*a(n), or of the form a(n+1) = 3*a(n) - k, where k is the last term of the previous doubling block. No proof of this phenomenon is known to the author.
%e A394252 a(1)=1.
%e A394252 For n=2, we must use exactly 1 earlier term {1}.
%e A394252 Representable numbers: 1.
%e A394252 The smallest integer >1 not representable is 2, so a(2)=2.
%e A394252 For n=3, we use exactly 2 terms from {1,2}.
%e A394252 Representable numbers: 2,3,4.
%e A394252 The smallest integer >2 not representable is 5, so a(3)=5.
%e A394252 For n=4, we use exactly 3 terms from {1,2,5}.
%e A394252 Representable numbers: 6,7,8,9.
%e A394252 The smallest integer >5 not representable is 10, so a(4)=10.
%o A394252 (Python)
%o A394252 from itertools import product
%o A394252 def representable(x,t,A):
%o A394252     for c in product(A, repeat=t):
%o A394252         if sum(c)==x:
%o A394252             return True
%o A394252     return False
%o A394252 def seq(n):
%o A394252     A=[1]
%o A394252     while len(A)<n:
%o A394252         k=A[-1]+1
%o A394252         while representable(k,len(A),A):
%o A394252             k+=1
%o A394252         A.append(k)
%o A394252     return A
%K A394252 nonn,new
%O A394252 1,2
